{"parse":{"title":"Topographic wetness index","pageid":43212772,"revid":821857336,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>topographic wetness index</b> (<b>TWI</b>), also known as the compound topographic index (CTI), is a steady state wetness index. It is commonly used to quantify topographic control on <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrology\" title=\"Hydrology\">hydrological</a> processes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sorensenetal2006_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sorensenetal2006-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  The index is a function of both the <a href=\"/wiki/Slope\" title=\"Slope\">slope</a> and the upstream contributing area per unit width <a href=\"/wiki/Orthogonal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Orthogonal\">orthogonal</a> to the flow direction. The index was designed for hillslope <a href=\"/wiki/Catena_(soil)\" title=\"Catena (soil)\">catenas</a>. Accumulation numbers in flat areas will be very large, so TWI will not be a relevant variable. The index is highly correlated with several soil attributes such as <a href=\"/wiki/Soil_horizon\" title=\"Soil horizon\">horizon</a> depth, <a href=\"/wiki/Silt\" title=\"Silt\">silt</a> percentage, organic matter content, and <a href=\"/wiki/Phosphorus\" title=\"Phosphorus\">phosphorus</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Moore1993_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Moore1993-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Methods of computing this index differ primarily in the way the upslope contributing area is calculated. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Definition\">Definition</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Topographic_wetness_index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Definition\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The topographic wetness index is defined as:\n</p><p><span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle \\ln {a \\over \\tan b}}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>ln</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mfrac>\n            <mi>a</mi>\n            <mrow>\n              <mi>tan</mi>\n              <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n              <mi>b</mi>\n            </mrow>\n          </mfrac>\n        </mrow>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle \\ln {a \\over \\tan b}}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/d5c045516d265fc8edc171f2c65ef91a2f85fad7\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -2.005ex; width:7.907ex; height:4.843ex;\" alt=\"{\\displaystyle \\ln {a \\over \\tan b}}\"/></span>\n</p><p>where <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle a}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>a</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle a}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/ffd2487510aa438433a2579450ab2b3d557e5edc\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.23ex; height:1.676ex;\" alt=\"a\"/></span> is the local upslope area draining through a certain point per unit <a href=\"/wiki/Contour_line\" title=\"Contour line\">contour</a> length and <span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle \\tan b}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>tan</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mi>b</mi>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle \\tan b}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/85b472918bc547cec2741fc3c556d46f52451e23\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:4.744ex; height:2.176ex;\" alt=\"{\\displaystyle \\tan b}\"/></span> is the local <a href=\"/wiki/Slope\" title=\"Slope\">slope</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Radian\" title=\"Radian\">radians</a>. The TWI has been used to study spatial scale effects on hydrological processes. The topographic wetness index (TWI) was developed by <a href=\"/wiki/Keith_Beven\" title=\"Keith Beven\">Beven</a> and Kirkby<sup id=\"cite_ref-BevenKirkby_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BevenKirkby-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> within the runoff model TOPMODEL. The topographic wetness index is unitless.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Uses\">Uses</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Topographic_wetness_index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Uses\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The TWI has been used to study spatial scale effects on <a href=\"/wiki/Hydrology\" title=\"Hydrology\">hydrological</a> processes and to identify hydrological flow paths for <a href=\"/wiki/Geochemistry\" title=\"Geochemistry\">geochemical</a> modelling, as well as to characterize biological processes such as annual <a href=\"/wiki/Primary_production\" title=\"Primary production\">net primary production</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Vegetation\" title=\"Vegetation\">vegetation</a> patterns, and forest site quality.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Topographic_wetness_index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Sorensenetal2006-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Sorensenetal2006_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">S\u00f8rensen, R.; Zinko, U.; Seibert, J. (2006). \"On the calculation of the topographic wetness index: evaluation of different methods based on field observations\". <i>Hydrology and Earth System Sciences</i>. <b>10</b>: 101\u2013112.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Hydrology+and+Earth+System+Sciences&amp;rft.atitle=On+the+calculation+of+the+topographic+wetness+index%3A+evaluation+of+different+methods+based+on+field+observations&amp;rft.volume=10&amp;rft.pages=101-112&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.aulast=S%C3%B8rensen&amp;rft.aufirst=R.&amp;rft.au=Zinko%2C+U.&amp;rft.au=Seibert%2C+J.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATopographic+wetness+index\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Moore1993-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Moore1993_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> <cite class=\"citation book\">Moore, I.D.; Gessler, P.E.; Nielsen, G.A.; Petersen, G.A (1993). \"Terrain attributes:  estimation methods and scale effects.\".  In Jakeman, A.J.; Beck, M.B.; McAleer, M. <i>Modelling Change in Environmental Systems</i>. London: Wiley. p.&#160;189 \u2013 214.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Terrain+attributes%3A++estimation+methods+and+scale+effects.&amp;rft.btitle=Modelling+Change+in+Environmental+Systems&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pages=189+-+214&amp;rft.pub=Wiley&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.aulast=Moore&amp;rft.aufirst=I.D.&amp;rft.au=Gessler%2C+P.E.&amp;rft.au=Nielsen%2C+G.A.&amp;rft.au=Petersen%2C+G.A&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATopographic+wetness+index\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-BevenKirkby-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-BevenKirkby_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a href=\"/wiki/Keith_Beven\" title=\"Keith Beven\">Beven, K.J.</a>; Kirkby, M. J. (1979). \"A physically based, variable contributing area model of basin hydrology\". <i>Hydrolological Science Bulletin</i>. <b>24</b> (1): 43\u201369. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1080/02626667909491834\">10.1080/02626667909491834</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Hydrolological+Science+Bulletin&amp;rft.atitle=A+physically+based%2C+variable+contributing+area+model+of+basin+hydrology&amp;rft.volume=24&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=43-69&amp;rft.date=1979&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F02626667909491834&amp;rft.aulast=Beven&amp;rft.aufirst=K.J.&amp;rft.au=Kirkby%2C+M.+J.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATopographic+wetness+index\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1332\nCached time: 20180908115644\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content